I headed over to Eden Green, Riverside Village this afternoon to put up some nets. Folks reached out through our online form about nets missing and I’m showing up, pulling up with my ladder, a few nets and a heart full of hope for the city. Sometimes you just gotta take action and take things into your own hands to make a difference on both large and small scales. 

I’ve never taken down a net on a court before or out one up. I felt like I was winning a championship while I was on that ladder.

I ran into some residents while I was out there and told them what I was up to. Rims are being taken down all over the city. A lot of the residents at Riverside Apartments agreed with me, They said “you’d think having rims would be a good thing.” I said, “I feel you.” Common sense ain’t that common, I thought.

How can you take everything away from people, including activities to have fun, and then expect them to stay out of trouble?

Anyhow, I ran into a few police officers that recognized my hoodie and asked if they could get a few bucket gardens we made for Earth Day. All and all, it was a great day in the city of wind. Great weather today. If you know a court in need, fill out our online form and we’ll pull up. If y’all want to make a donation, feel free to do that too. #savestreetball #writersofinstagram #basketball #love

I went to three parks this morning and noticed that the tennis nets and soccer goals were up, but they took down the basketball rims. Come on man! Chicago Park Districts need to put all the hoops back up in the City. Parks are for everybody! #savestreetball

I saw a young man sleeping underneath a slide at Cole park. He saw me shooting hoops and he walked over to play with me. I asked him why he didn’t have any shoes and he said he just got out of incarceration. I said “they just let you out of jail with no shoes or money? He said yeah. 

He’d been in solitary confinement for two months but it was cool, all he needed was a window and some air.

I asked him has he tried to stay in any shelters or if the jail had offered him and pointers for re-adjustment or some type of pathway anywhere except right back to jail. He said “no.” “All I really need is some shoes, shower and a meal.

What’d you go to jail for anyway man. I’m just trying to make small talk. He says he was locked up because he liked stealing cars and driving fast. 

I said “aw man I’ve been hearing a lot about carjackings. What kind of car did you steal.” He said he stole a mustang, so I asked how! He said “easy man, I just broke the window, popped off the ignition cap, saw a red and blue wire, twisted those b’s together and it started up.”

I said, wow, you sound like a Microsoft engineer right now. The kid was shocked and said “really,” I said really.

I wanted to help him out so I took him down the street to city sports to get some shoes. He wanted some Jordan’s so I bought them for him. I also gave him $50 and he told me to drop him off at McDonalds. He said he just wanted to use the Wi-Fi. Kids are going to McDonald’s to use the Wi-Fi.

I’m telling you this story because that’s what happens when you’re in the neighborhood. When you’re involved and you care. You go out thinking you’re going to shoot hoops, but you go home learning about the problems with our prison system. They left a kid out on the street with no shoes and no money.

quite frankly, we need to make sure we are investing in these kids before they even get to the point of stealing cars. I’m talking about education reform, mental health clinics, food access, all of it.

I’m out here putting up rims and nets so we create more opportunities for connection and positive mentorship. Learn more about our #savestreetball via 🔗in bio. #savestreetball writersofinstagram #love #basketball

I’ve had the privilege of meeting so many @depaulu graduates over the last few years. DePaul graduates are doing great work in the city as social workers, community organizers, non profit leaders and more. We’ll have a conversation and I’ll end up saying, where’d you go to school and they all say I graduated from DePaul. I’ve come to expect that response because I’ve heard it so often by so many good hearted people.

Today, I’m proud to announce that I’m joining this cohort of humanitarians. I’m honored to have received a Doctorate of Humane Letters from DePaul University. 

I’m so grateful, not only because of the prestige of this university but also because of the awesomeness of the man the university was named after, Saint Vincent de Paul. I’m not catholic but I can connect with him and this place. I would call him a great man but a legendary Chicago activist Rudy Lozano said there are no great men or women in this world. There are only ordinary people that take on big challenges. Saint Vincent de Paul definitely made an impact in the world. You all have to read up on all of his accomplishments. 

I remember being embarrassed to eat at catholic shelters growing up. The food was excellent but I was embarrassed that my classmates were volunteering to pass out food to me. I’m grateful now to have had that experience. It’s interesting to think that the whole volunteer food shelter concept was pioneered by Saint Vincent de Paul. Its an honor to have my name Cole associated with DePaul. 

I hear there’s a tour in France you can take to visit all of the places DePaul blessed with his servant leadership. I’d like to take that trip one day to be able to walk in his shoes.

Overall I’m just grateful that God allows me to serve alongside amazing people in the city I love. Thank you to my family for always supporting my big dreams and big ideas. Thank you to my team at M3, the board and all of our volunteers and supporters. Congrats to the 2023 Class of DePaul graduates. Let’s Keep making waves out here. #saintvincentdepaul #depaul #graduation #doctoratedegree

All of this gun violence is on my mind. Seeing these social media videos is terrifying. People run down on folks with automatic rifles. Bullets are fast already, now it’s like you have to run from the bullet and a person running a lightning fast cone drill at you spraying at you. 

The world just stops and you feel like you’re in a movie; Your last performance on earth. Bro, I don’t give speeches just to give speeches. I’m dead serious about my message and what I’m saying. 

We say stuff like be safe and be careful. Saying things like that should not be regular. It’s almost like I’m just going to start saying, I love you to people. This gun violence is not regular, man. 

I don’t do non profit work. This is God’s work and it’s a calling. When you’re called to do this work, you can’t do just one thing. #besafe #chicago #gunviolence #god #guns

2 Miles to Freedom 

I didn’t have too good of a showing yesterday on my two mile jog. Today, I was determined not to take any breaks and just control my pace and feelings throughout. I wore my Juneteenth shirt today and I purposely jogged down Western because I wanted to wave the flag, per se. 

The Red - signifies the blood of those killed for the cause of the African community, throughout history. The Gold – signifies the vast wealth and riches which belong to the African continent. The Green – signifies the lushness and hope of the Earth namely that of the Promised Land of Ethiopia. 

I’m also using these runs to educate myself. I'm a big fan of the @wbezchicago podcast, Reset by Sasha. I listen to a lot of podcasts while on runs; Building up my physical and mental endurance at the same time. Today's podcast was about reparations and turning ideas into policy. I know ideas are powerful weapons and tools that can change the world. I truly hope I have a seat at the table when it comes to what reparations will look like in Chicago. I definitely want to be a part of great decisions being made.

As I jogged and started experiencing a little fatigue, I thought about being a runaway slave and running through the woods to freedom. Since my run today is two miles long, I motivated myself by thinking I only had two miles until I’d cross a border into freedom. That thought made me speed up a little but mostly it made me steady. I didn’t want to show any fatigue in my facial expression. I was locked into this metaphor. I thought about all the people that I hoped to bring along with me. There was no time to be tired, gotta suck it up. I could definitely see myself living that way. Taking a stand with integrity for the truth that best represents my tribe.

On the back of my M3 Juneteenth T-shirt it says a Frederick Douglas quote, “I prayed for freedom for 20 years but didn’t get an answer until I prayed with my legs.” As I jogged for mental and physical health, I thought that quote really went in well. You have to wake up and take action. You have to learn from the firing line of experience, but take action. #happyjuneteenth Grab a M3 #juneteenth shirt 🔗in bio

They’re teaching high school and college courses off the book I wrote entitled It's Not Regular: How to Recognize Injustice Hidden in Plain Sight?

A lot of people are beginning to say “it’s not normal” to see bullet proof glass or the shot spotter technology on poles, or 15 currency exchanges in the neighborhood and no banks, or all the cough syrup locked up at stores. I could have called the book " it's not normal” but I didn’t do that because my family from Statesville would hit me up all the time about what’s not “regular.”

The same issues that I drew attention to over five years ago when I wrote It's Not Regular: How to Recognize Injustice Hidden in Plain Sight? are still prevalent today. My Block My Hood My City continues to work vigorously to combat them every day. #itsnotregular

When I’m asked to speak on panels, it’s always an opportunity to connect with others I typically don’t have in my contacts. Working in #foodjustice we are still in siloes, often working on what’s important to what’s in front of them rather than the global impact we could make if we worked together.

After sitting on the Food Justice panel for @foodbank’s Empowering Eaters: Access, Affordability and Healthy Choices, I met @drdavenayak - a physican, a farmer and a deacon. He donates the majority of his crop each year and offered to provide their corn for our next food giveaways.

This work is a calling for all of us working to bring resources to our communities.

Today I saw a teenager hooping in my backyard. I came out to speak with him, not to kick him off my court, just to build. Turns out he’s a junior at butler college prep and wants to work on his game, but there’s no rims up at any of the courts near where he lives. They’ve all been taken down, or the concrete on the court has potholes.

We chopped it up for a good minute, about life, about hoops. He said he’s received a few looks from colleges but mostly HBCU’s. He didn’t know if he wanted to go that route. I asked him which HBCU’s had been in touch with him. He said Howard University. I said man that’s an amazing opportunity. Go for it! 

We exchanged numbers and I told him that he could hoop in my backyard anytime. Text me or call and let me know first and I may come out and hoop too.

Look at God, man. To me it doesn’t make sense to take down basketball hoops in Chicago in an effort to prevent violence. There’s no evidence correlating taking down hoops to increasing neighborhood safety. If you catch somebody smoking weed on a park bench, you don’t take away the bench to stop them from smoking weed. That’s really the best way to sum up what we’re doing by putting rims back up. Please continue to support our save Save Street Ball initiative because we are saving lives by keeping courts active. #savestreetball #writersofinstagram #jahmalcole

“Each time a man stands up for an ideal, or acts to improve the lot of others, or strikes out against injustice, he sends forth a tiny ripple of hope, and crossing each other from a million different centers of energy and daring those ripples build a current which can sweep down the mightiest walls of oppression and resistance.” RFK #savestreetball

Brandon, David and a few other popular St. Joes players used to pull up to Lincoln Park in a Chevy Envoy. It may as well have been a Maybach to me. The whole hood was watching. The pick up games were already lit, but when the St. Joes boys pulled up, the stakes would change, the air got thinner. Scoring a bucket against them would boost not only your confidence, but your popularity. 

I used to see Brandon in the hood sporadically. I went to an alternative high school and he attended a catholic school. Sometimes, his sister would drop all the kids in the hood off at home after school. I would have her drop me off at the corner store. I didn’t want anybody to know I lived in a motel. “Motel Hell” as my pops called it. 

Every so often, I would see Brandon drive by in the hood and he would see me playing at a court by myself. He loves hooping so, he would jump out the Envoy and play me one on one in his flip flops. This was before crocks. He would jump out and just play me until it got too dark. His fundamentals are what I remember. I think he just used these one on one games with me to practice his left hand, he was way better at ball than me. 

Warming up at Lincoln Park, we would shoot for captains, like who would pick the teams. Then, we would all basically do warm up layups or dunks. I was determined to show out so I wanted to practice my in between the legs dunk. My first attempt was really just a warm up. I jogged to the rim and did a basic right handed dunk. Of all people, Brandon said, “man that’s regular, don’t hold up the line for that”. He was right, it was. I was just gauging my timing though. My next practice dunk, I did through the legs, missed it but got close. Brandon said “damn, okay.” Then, he picked me up on his team. I probably played the worst game of my life because I was so nervous playing with the St. Joe's bunch but I still remember that day at Lincoln Park. 

Support #savestreetball https://formyblock.salsalabs.org/SaveStreetBall to help ensure that everyone has opportunity and access to play, hoop, learn and grow. #lebron20 #writersofinstagram #love #growth #basketball #lincolnpark #living #friends

Food for the Soul

“Anybody home, want some food,” is what I kept yelling as I drove by tents pitched all around Lower Wacker Drive. It was on my heart to pass out food and hoodies to the homeless population that lives down here. I heard there may be around 5,000 Chicagoans down here laying in sleeping bags and tents. A lot of attention is being placed on migrants coming to the city from Venezuela and all over. I see police departments letting migrants sleep inside the station and getting them food, ppe, hats etc. It is kind and necessary. We also can’t forget about the homeless population on Lower Wacker Drive. They've been here for so many years. 

I love Chicago because there are so many dope people passing out backpacks for kids going back to school and so many social impact organizations that focus on different needs. I know the night ministry specifically comes down to Lower Wacker Drive and provides food and clean needles. What I'm doing today is not really an initiative of my organization, this was just on my heart to do, not trying to win no awards, just doing what I love, playing my part. 

I bought 15 home cooked meals from Mz. Ellen’s Sunday Dinner Cafe. She’s adopted me with love in Chatham and calls me son; I call her mom. She prays for me and calls me every time I'm on the news. She’s watched me build an organization over the past ten years, she’s seen my struggles etc. She made Turkey Meatloaf with Spinach W/Mushroom Gravy, Garlic Mashed Potatoes, Cabbage, Red Beans & Rice, Corn on the Cob, Corn Bread, with Gravy on the side for the Mashed Potatoes. She takes orders on Friday and you can pick them up Sunday. Call, text or message her at 773-606-5845 if you want to support or you need Sunday Dinner, food for the soul, creating my tiny ripple of hope in the city I love. 

#happymonday #love #food #chicago #homelessness

Paradise on Merrill 

The name of the block precedes itself. After walking and building with the President of the block club, she told me that she couldn't stand the name Murder Merrill and “words have power.” She created a block club and a garden on the same block and changed the name to Paradise on Merrill. 

In the garden, she has everything you need from greens to asparagus. Garlic, rosemary etc. Black males from the community work the garden and children in the nearby schools that have never eaten veggies, now pick veggies in her garden. 
What used to be known as a high drug trafficking block has “calmed down a lot” she says. I love her organizing strategy. She basically just started looking people in the eye and talking to them. She has an aura about her. She said to the block boys, if you’re trying to coexist with us, you need to respect us. The drug dealers didn't leave completely but they left when she was working on the garden or when she brought people to the garden. 

When a new property lender bought a building on the block, she met with the broker and asked him to sell the building to someone that can respect us. Then, when the new owner would come, she would let him know that they inherited a drug portal and that they need more cameras and lights. 

There’s a school on the block, so children are traumatized when they see this type of behavior.  She started an after school program where she feeds students dinner after school because kids aren't getting fed, they’re getting breakfast and lunch at school but they need dinner. I love her philosophy to just be a good person. You don’t have to be on local school councils to be engaged. You don’t have to be working in politics to make a difference. 
We need support for our block club program to help ensure that the kind of community impact that Paradise on Merrill is creating continues to be magnified. #writersofinstagram #garden

Some say it’s activism, some say it’s organizing, some say it’s philanthropy. For me, it’s just life. This work chooses you. It chose me, for sure. I’ve been answering the calls and showing up for over ten years, my friends say I’ve been this person my whole life. I had other interests, passions, but I’ve always felt most motivated in this lane that God carved out for me. I don’t do this for likes or pats on the back. I don't do it for money or to be elected. It’s just natural for me. Service from the heart. It’s been a faith walk. You are never fully equipped and God knows that. I laugh at how under-equipped, under-educated and under-connected I am. I still move forward. The road is so narrow that I can’t turn around. I think I’ll let fear go; It takes too much energy away from the direction that I’m headed. #writersofinstagram

3,000 Chandeliers 

I am honored to have had the opportunity to speak at yesterday's International Downtown Association event. The Palmer House provided a magnificent setting with around 3,000 chandeliers, and the energy of my fellow speakers was just as vibrant. The event covered great topics and featured amazing people.

The first speaker of the day was Robin Rue Simmons. Robin is the Founder and Executive Director of FirstRepair, a not-for-profit organization dedicated to advancing local reparations on a national scale. Robin shared how active reparations are making a difference in Evanston, providing a direct benefit of $25,000 to build wealth through home equity for eligible Black residents who lived in Evanston during the period of harm from 1919 to 1969 or their direct descendants. 

Before I took the stage, I had a chance to speak with Robin, and she shared details about the amount of money being disbursed. I expressed my excitement, which surprised her, as most people tend to ask, "Why isn't more money being disbursed?" I hugged her and told her that she's leading the way. It was an incredible moment, and I truly appreciate being around progress and positivity.

During my presentation, I talked about the importance of bringing holiday lights to King Drive. I questioned how downtown can be so magnificent if it wasn't created for everyone to enjoy. It's not right that festive lights adorn downtown while, in our neighborhoods, all we see are police car lights and helicopter lights. Something as simple as hanging holiday lights can inspire hope and interrupt the trauma that kids in the inner city are experiencing. I encouraged the audience to support my non-profit's mission of lighting up 500 homes on King Drive by making a donation or checking out our Amazon wish list. Additionally, I extended an invitation for anyone interested to come and help us hang some lights.

There's so much more I could share, but in essence, I want to express my gratitude to the @loopchicago for hosting me as a speaker. Please keep booking me; I have a message to share with the world. #publicspeaking #writersofinstagram #lights #chandelier #reparations

I came up eating at Aldi's; putting the quarter in the cart outside, eating Salisbury steaks, Sherbert Ice cream, Black Cherry Pop. Mom's favorite pop was cream soda. Crazy how nowadays I rarely drink #pop but when I do, I take a sip, and the taste always brings me back to the springtime of my youth. I think about my grandma when I drink Dr. Pepper, and my mom when I drink Aldi Cream Soda.

I think we shopped at Aldi because the prices were good and they accepted food stamps. We used to get booklets of those. I swear I didn't know a food stamp wasn't real money until I put one in a pop machine and it broke. That's how I found out I was on welfare. I was like 6 or 7 years old.

My mom used to give me, my brother, and my sister each a food stamp and tell us to spend 10 cents and bring her back two dollars and seventy cents so she could use the cash to buy bleach. You couldn't use food stamps for basic toiletries.

Anyhow, now ALDI Corp is one of the lead contributors to my block, my hood, my city. Huge thank you to the folks at @aldiusa for supporting our work. I used to put the quarter in the **cart** to get the cart, now y'all put dollars into my **community** to push the community forward. I brought a quarter and a hoodie for everybody before I started the presentation. Feels good to remember where you came from and be supported as you navigate to where you're going. Huge shout out to my mom for all she poured into us kids. #writersofinstagram #motivation #nonprofit #support #lovequotes #love #life #food #donations

I’d like to emphasize that the struggles faced by Black and Brown communities in Chicago against white supremacy share striking similarities with the Palestinian resistance against Israel. We owe a debt of gratitude to the civil rights movement, which has provided us with affirmative action, the promise of equality, prohibitions on discrimination in public places, integration in schools and public facilities, and laws against employment discrimination. I hold hope that a similar framework can one day be achieved in the Middle East. However, even with the passage of civil rights legislation in America 60 years ago, deliberate outright oppression still lingers, though it now takes on more subtle and structural forms. It’s not as overt and 161 lynchings per year, but it’s still cruel. It’s not as evil as sicking German shepherds at crowds of people but it’s structural. #gaza #isreal #palestine #chicago #civilrights #mlk #oppression #jahmalcole #whitesupremecy #writersofinstagram @shaunking

I want to help you become more involved!

When comparing the corporate giving landscape in 2023 to a few years back, I sense a diversity, equity, and inclusion fatigue. In simpler terms, there's a giving drought. We can all feel it. In the morning, I try to bury my worries and fears with as much gratitude as possible. I'm truly grateful to have come this far. However, as I keep moving, there's not much time for personal feelings. There are too many people suffering and too many people who need our immediate support.

My purpose in life is to do something about it. The work that my organization does has been recognized, from the Forbes article below to the Today Show. I'm going to work with more corporations one-on-one so they can support the work of social impact organizations in my city and the world. Bring me in for a "Where Do I Start" workshop. You can book me for a few hours or even a lunchtime presentation. I don't need a fancy setup or anything.

I want to come talk to people at corporations about how to get involved and where to start. The number one question I'm asked is, "Where do I start?" My organization is an "on-ramp" to community engagement. I'm happy to teach you how to get engaged with nonprofit organizations in your city for the long term.

I know you understand the injustice being denied. I know you understand that people want to work for socially engaged corporations. I know you care. So do I. It takes all of us. We need partners in business, government, and nonprofits. We've got to work together, y'all. #workshop #dei #diversityequityinclusion #nonprofits #givingtuesday #corporategiving #gratitude #love #support

When the Puerto Rican flag illuminated Humboldt Park, I witnessed smiles on people’s faces. Unity graced Division Street, and I observed a sense of togetherness. Those same radiant smiles adorned the faces of children in Chatham during the tree lighting ceremony on 83rd and King. The identical joy reflected on the faces of kids footworking in front of the 30-ft holiday tree in Bronzeville on 35th. The same light illuminated the faces of children standing before a 15-ft tree in front of Altgeld Gardens. Kudos to my man, Waddy.

From Englewood to North Lawndale, to Washington Park, people throughout the city have begun adorning their own neighborhoods with lights. No longer is downtown the exclusive haven for magnificence.

I love it, man. I genuinely believe that simple acts like hanging lights can mitigate blight. Amidst the helicopter lights and police car lights, children now get to experience the joy of holiday lights. How does that make a person feel? Deion Sanders says, “You look good, you feel good. You feel good, you do good.” How does that quote resonate for the community? If your community looks good, you feel good. Feeling good fosters pride in your block and neighborhood. Deion, we need your support—please consider donating.

Help us keep the lights on at My Block, My Hood, My City. While we may not have the means to illuminate the entire city, we will persist in finding ways for you to get involved and take action to enhance your block. We’re committed to showing up and making a positive impact. #life #lights #hope #holiday #holidays #chicago #magnificent #myblockmyhoodmycity #community #citypride #unity #kindness #smile

King’s Energy

Today I took a walk down the same block that Dr. King grew up on, in the Sweet Auburn community. 

In the early 1900’s this was a predominantly African American block, with African American cooks, laundresses, candy makers, maids and dress makers. For me, walking on the same cobblestone as Dr. King was an honor. The thought that Dr. King had once walked in this same direction and the ATL sunshine graced his face as it did mine this morning was inspirational. I thought, “MLK walked this way. MLK lived on the block.” Before I even stepped a foot inside the actual King Center, I was already inspired. 

I came to the MLK center today for a few reasons. First to get some writing done in my new book. However, I quickly veered from that plan when I got out on King’s actual block. As soon as I saw the first mural, I decided right then to let go of any expectations for the day. My goal is now to be as present as possible. Today would be about learning and absorbing as much “King Energy” as I could. Then later on, God willing, I’ll take that energy with me and write more inspired words at another time. 

This happens in #nature with plants, it’s called photosynthesis. The process by which green plants use sunlight to synthesize foods from carbon dioxide and water. If I’m not mistaken, oxygen is the byproduct of photosynthesis. In my case, good writing and good decisions will be the byproduct of me being present while visiting the King Center.

It’s Up!

Someone just sent me this photo of a mural on Blackhawk Street at the entrance of @saltshedchicago . This is what it looks like when hard work pays off!

I began this organization through volunteering. I am proud to be on a mural, surrounded by volunteers. Our mission is to care for people, no matter what. I keep saying that we’re like the Red Cross of the Hood, the New United Way. Essentially, we are the emergency response to what happens in the community. If something goes wrong in the city, our volunteers are on the front line, ready to step in. Whether it’s shoveling snow, removing garbage from a flooded home, hanging holiday lights in areas that need illumination, or distributing food to the community when a big business suddenly leaves, we possess a skillset of #resilience in times of crisis.

I believe that doing small things is a mature way to approach service. I was trying to help clean up my block; I didn’t set out to be on a billboard. My team keeps showing up; they didn’t set out to be on a billboard. Our #volunteers keep showing up; they didn’t set out to be on a billboard. Just proud to be living, man. Proud to be walking in my purpose.

Shoutout to Stizo and @wintrust for making this happen. More details coming soon!
